You can’t realistically live on free tiers forever with React + FastAPI if you want Vriddhi to become a serious product with paying users. Free tiers are fantastic for prototyping, demos, or personal use — but they come with hard limits:

🚫 Limitations of Free Tiers
Timeouts: you already noticed the 15-minute timeout (common in Vercel/Render free dynos). That kills UX for financial apps where users may sit with the app open.

Cold starts: when nobody uses your app for a while, free instances “sleep.” First user after idle waits ~30+ seconds.

Resource caps: free tiers often limit RAM (0.5–1 GB), disk (512 MB–1 GB), and CPU. Financial simulations/optimizations can easily exceed this.

Concurrent users: most free tiers only support a handful of simultaneous connections before requests queue/timeout.

No SLAs: you get no uptime guarantees, no monitoring, no alerts.

✅ When Paid Tiers Make Sense
Move to paid when you hit any of these triggers:

Monetization starts → once people are paying, you don’t want downtime ruining trust.

Active user base grows → >50–100 active users per day will choke free tiers.

Performance pain → if background optimization jobs or API responses start slowing down.

Compliance needs → secure auth, encrypted DBs, or logging usually require paid plans.

⚡ My Recommendation
MVP (now) → keep Streamlit Cloud free for your main app (low friction, great charts, simple auth).

Parallel React/FastAPI → stay on free tiers while experimenting and refining UX.

Upgrade to Render/Vercel Pro + a managed Postgres (e.g., Supabase, Neon) once you:

have ~1000+ monthly active users, or

earn even $200–500/month in subscriptions.

That way, infra is always covered by revenue, not out of pocket.

